---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import ToolSchema from "../../components/ToolSchema.astro";
import RelatedTools from "../../components/RelatedTools.astro";
import Breadcrumbs from "../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro";

const faqs = [
  { question: "Western Zodiac", answer: "♑ Capricorn Element: Earth | Rulership: Saturn" },
  { question: "Chinese Zodiac", answer: "🐎 Horse Yin/Yang: Yang | Element: Fire" },
  { question: "Life-Stage Milestones", answer: "About the Age Calculator: Exact Date Calculations & Astrology Determining someone's exact age is a deceptively simple mathematical challenge. Because months differ in duration (from 28 to 31 days) and leap years inject an extra day into February every four years, simply dividing the total number of milliseconds by a generic year duration leads to off-by-one errors. This exact age calculator is built using correct calendar-date math to accurately calculate years, months, and days, ensuring precise tracking." },
  { question: "Zodiac and Astrological Boundary Determinations", answer: "This tool goes beyond basic years and months arithmetic by computing astrological alignments:" },
  { question: "Understanding Leap Years in Date Math", answer: "A common bug in date arithmetic is the handling of leap days. The year 2000 was a leap year, containing 366 days, while 2001 was not. If a person born on February 29, 2000, measures their age on February 28, 2001, they are technically 364 days old. Since February 29 does not exist in 2001, standard systems must determine if the user turns one full year old on February 28 or March 1. This system uses calendar logic, completing the year boundary on the transition to March 1 in non-leap years." },
  { question: "Privacy & Execution", answer: "None of your personal birth information is ever uploaded to a database or shared. All computations execute on your local device within the client browser window. You can freely model dates for historical queries or project future ages safe in the knowledge that your data remains 100% private." },
  { question: "How Exact Age Calculations Handle Calendar Anomalies", answer: "Calculating age down to the day is a deceptively simple mathematical challenge due to calendar anomalies. Gregorian calendar months vary in length between 28, 29, 30, and 31 days. When calculating the difference between two dates—such as February 29 on a leap year and March 1 on a non-leap year—a standard difference calculation will yield slight variances. Our calculator uses a logical calendar subtraction algorithm that adjusts for the number of days in the preceding month, borrowing days when necessary to ensure the result matches standard legal and biological age metrics." },
  { question: "Legal Significance of Age Milestones Across Countries", answer: "Age calculation has significant legal implications globally, establishing boundaries for legal rights and responsibilities. The age of majority—the threshold where an individual is legally recognized as an adult—is set at 18 in most countries, though it is 19 in Alabama and Nebraska, and 21 in Mississippi. Other legal milestones include the age of consent, driving eligibility, voting rights, and the minimum age for purchasing alcohol or tobacco. Using an age calculator helps verify compliance with legal requirements for employment contracts and age-restricted transactions." },
  { question: "Chronological Age vs. Biological Age", answer: "While this tool calculates your chronological age—the exact duration since your birth date—scientists also track biological age. Biological age refers to the physiological wear and tear on your cells and organs. It is influenced by genetics, lifestyle habits, diet, exercise, and stress levels. While two individuals may share the exact same chronological age of 45, their biological ages could differ by over a decade. Biological age is measured using epigenetic biomarkers and DNA methylation tests." },
  { question: "Calculating Half-Birthday Milestones and Anniversaries", answer: "Many individuals track secondary milestones such as half-birthdays (exactly six months after your birth date) or the number of days lived (such as celebrating your 10,000th or 20,000th day on earth). Our age calculator makes it easy to compute these exact milestones. This is particularly popular for organizing unique milestone parties, tracking infant age intervals in months for pediatric checkups, and coordinating project deadlines based on the elapsed time from a specific start date." },
  { question: "Related Utility Tools", answer: "GPA Calculator Calculate your grade point average based on class weights and credits." }
];
